  "prompt": "What if a cricket ball hits a batsman\u2019s helmet and then goes to the boundary?",
  "response": "If a cricket ball hits a batsman\u2019s helmet and then goes to the boundary, the following rules apply:\n\n1. **Five Penalty Runs**: The batting team is awarded **five penalty runs**. This is because the helmet is considered a protective gear placed on the field by the fielding team, and hitting it is penalized.\n\n2. **Boundary Runs**: In addition to the five penalty runs, the runs scored from the ball reaching the boundary (either **four** or **six**) are also counted. \n\n3. **Total Runs**: The total runs awarded to the batting team would be the sum of the penalty runs and the boundary runs. For example:\n   - If the ball hits the helmet and goes for a four, the batting team gets **5 (penalty) + 4 (boundary) = 9 runs**.\n   - If the ball hits the helmet and goes for a six, the batting team gets **5 (penalty) + 6 (boundary) = 11 runs**.\n\n4. **Batsman\u2019s Contribution**: The runs are not credited to the batsman\u2019s individual score unless they hit the ball. If the ball deflects off the batsman\u2019s body or bat and then hits the helmet, the runs would be credited to the batsman. \n\nThis rule is in place to ensure that the fielding team is cautious about where they place protective gear on the field.",
